{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16216"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16216"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.01,0.05,0.02,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64368"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8907"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16216"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49800"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4168"},{"type":"tags","id":"4170"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21198"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64368"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with progressive abdominal pain and shortness of breath over three days. She underwent in vitro fertilisation (IVF) treatment two weeks ago. She has no significant medical history and takes only folic acid supplements. She works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended and tender. There are reduced breath sounds at both lung bases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum beta-human chorionic gonadotropin: 850 IU/L (positive)\u003Cbr /\u003EHaemoglobin: 165 g/L (115-160)\u003Cbr /\u003EHaematocrit: 0.52 (0.36-0.46)\u003Cbr /\u003ESodium: 133 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium: 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 120 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlbumin: 28 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ectopic pregnancy","Ovarian torsion","Ruptured ovarian cyst","Pelvic inflammatory disease","Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of late ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome (OHSS), a serious complication of fertility treatment. The timing (two weeks post-IVF), positive pregnancy test, and constellation of symptoms and signs including abdominal pain, dyspnoea, ascites, and pleural effusions are characteristic. Laboratory findings show haemoconcentration (elevated haematocrit), hypoalbuminaemia, and electrolyte disturbances, which are hallmark features of OHSS due to increased vascular permeability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian hyperstimulation syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in two forms: early (within 9 days of hCG trigger) and late (9-14 days after trigger, in the setting of pregnancy). Late OHSS, as seen here, tends to be more severe due to ongoing hCG stimulation from pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E would be a consideration in any pregnant patient with abdominal pain post-IVF. However, the systemic features, bilateral pleural effusions, and laboratory abnormalities are more consistent with OHSS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian torsion\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset, severe unilateral pain and vomiting. The gradual onset and bilateral nature of symptoms make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic inflammatory disease\u003C/strong\u003E would be unusual in the context of IVF and typically presents with fever, vaginal discharge, and bilateral adnexal tenderness without the systemic features seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERuptured ovarian cyst\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes acute, unilateral pain and would not explain the systemic features, pleural effusions, or laboratory abnormalities seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of OHSS involves careful fluid management, thromboprophylaxis, and monitoring for complications including renal impairment and thromboembolism. Severe cases may require paracentesis for symptomatic relief.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome (OHSS) is a serious complication of fertility treatment characterised by increased vascular permeability.","Late OHSS occurs 9-14 days after hCG trigger in pregnancy and is typically more severe than early OHSS.","Key features of severe OHSS include ascites, pleural effusions, haemoconcentration, and electrolyte disturbances."],"references":["Choe J, Shanks AL. In vitro fertilization [Internet]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 22]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562266/","Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RCOG). Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2022 [cited 2024 Nov 22]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/for-the-public/browse-our-patient-information/ovarian-hyperstimulation-syndrome/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16216"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49800"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T14:19:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T14:21:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8907"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64368"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"da